title: Equinumerosity of sets of relations and maps
content: Because ` ( ( 2o ^m B ) ^m A ) ~~ ( 2o ^m ( A X. B ) ) ~~ ` ` ( ( 2o ^m A ) ^m B ) ` is an instance of the law of exponents: ` ( ( C ^m B ) ^m A ) ~~ ( C ^m ( A X. B ) ) ~~ ( ( C ^m A ) ^m B ) ` we are led to see that ` ( ~P B ^m A ) ~~ ~P ( A X. B ) ~~ ( ~P A ^m B ) ` is true for any two sets, ` A ` and ` B ` , and thus there exist one-to-one onto relations between each of these three sets of relations.

blocks.name: enrelmap
blocks.content: The set of all possible relations between two sets is equinumerous to the set of all mappings from one set to the powerset of the other. See ~ rfovf1od for a demonstration of a natural one-to-one onto mapping. (Contributed by RP, 27-Apr-2021.)

blocks.name: enmappw
blocks.content: The set of all mappings from one set to the powerset of the other is equinumerous to the set of all mappings from the second set to the powerset of the first. (Contributed by RP, 27-Apr-2021.)

blocks.name: enmappwid
blocks.content: The set of all mappings from the powerset to the powerset is equinumerous to the set of all mappings from the set to the powerset of the powerset. (Contributed by RP, 27-Apr-2021.)

  -| wi(w0, wcel(c2, c4))

  -| diffss(s1, s4)

  -| diffsw(s1, w0)
  -| diffsw(s2, w0)
  -| diffsw(s3, w0)
} = {
  sylanbrc(w0, wf1o(c0, co(cpw(c1), cmap, c2), co(cpw(c2), cmap, c1)), wfn(c0, co(cpw(c1), cmap, c2)), wfn(ccnv(c0), co(cpw(c2), cmap, c1)))
  ffnd(c0, co(cpw(c1), cmap, c2), co(cpw(c2), cmap, c1), w0)
  fsovfd(s0, s1, s2, s3, s4, c0, c1, c2, c3, c4, c5, w0)
  mpbird(w0, wfn(ccnv(c0), co(cpw(c2), cmap, c1)), wfn(co(c1, c3, c2), co(cpw(c2), cmap, c1)))
  ffnd(co(c1, c3, c2), co(cpw(c2), cmap, c1), co(cpw(c1), cmap, c2), w0)
  fsovfd(s0, s1, s2, s3, s4, co(c1, c3, c2), c2, c1, c3, c5, c4, w0)
  fneq1d(ccnv(c0), co(cpw(c2), cmap, c1), co(c1, c3, c2), w0)
  fsovcnvd(s0, s1, s2, s3, s4, c0, co(c1, c3, c2), c3, c2, c4, c1, c5, w0)
  eqid(co(c1, c3, c2))

blocks.content: For any base set ` B ` the duality operator for self-mappings of subsets of that base set is one-to-one and onto. (Contributed by RP, 21-Apr-2021.)

  syl2anc(w0, (c0 :(P(c1)[‚Ü¶]P(c1))‚Üî(P(c1)[‚Ü¶]P(c1))), c0[Fn](P(c1)[‚Ü¶]P(c1)), `' c0 = c0)

  dssmapfvd(s1, s2, s0, c0, c1, c2, c3, w0)

  pwexd(c1, c3, w0)
  mptexg(s2, P(c1), universe, (c1 \(s1 `(c1 \ s2))))

  nfcv(s1, (P(c1)[‚Ü¶]P(c1)))

  fneq1(c0, (s1 ‚àà(P(c1)[‚Ü¶]P(c1))‚Ü¶(s2 ‚àà P(c1)‚Ü¶(c1 \(s1 `(c1 \ s2))))), (P(c1)[‚Ü¶]P(c1)))
  dssmapnvod(s0, s1, s2, c0, c2, c1, c3, w0)

blocks.name: dssmap2d
blocks.content: For any base set ` B ` the duality operator for self-mappings of subsets of that base set when composed with itself is the restricted identity operator. (Contributed by RP, 21-Apr-2021.)

thm dssmap2d(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, wceq(ccom(c0, c0), cres(cid, co(cpw(c1), cmap, cpw(c1)))))
  -| wceq(c2, cmpt(s0, universe, cmpt(s1, co(cpw(cv(s0)), cmap, cpw(cv(s0))), cmpt(s2, cpw(cv(s0)), cdif(cv(s0), cfv(cv(s1), cdif(cv(s0), cv(s2))))))))
  -| wceq(c0, cfv(c2, c1))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c1, c3))
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
  -| diffss(s1, s2)
  -| diffsc(s0, c1)
  -| diffsc(s1, c1)
  -| diffsc(s2, c1)
  -| diffsw(s0, w0)
  -| diffsw(s1, w0)
  -| diffsw(s2, w0)
} = {
  eqtr3d(ccom(c0, c0), cres(cid, co(cpw(c1), cmap, cpw(c1))), ccom(ccnv(c0), c0), w0)
  coeq1d(ccnv(c0), c0, c0, w0)
  dssmapnvod(s0, s1, s2, c0, c2, c1, c3, w0)
  syl(w0, wceq(ccom(ccnv(c0), c0), cres(cid, co(cpw(c1), cmap, cpw(c1)))), wf1o(c0, co(cpw(c1), cmap, cpw(c1)), co(cpw(c1), cmap, cpw(c1))))
  dssmapf1od(s0, s1, s2, c0, c1, c2, c3, w0)
  f1ococnv1(c0, co(cpw(c1), cmap, cpw(c1)), co(cpw(c1), cmap, cpw(c1)))
}
